    <text>
        <body>
             <div type="edition" subtype="ogham" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="pgl-Ogam" resp="#POC"><!--update lang and resp here-->              
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1" style="text-direction:up"/><persName><gap reason="damage" unit="stroke" extent="unknown"/><unclear reason="worn">ᚉ</unclear>ᚉᚔ <w type="formula" lemma="maqqas">ᚋᚐᚊ</w><gap reason="damage" unit="stroke" extent="unknown"/>
                    <lb n="2" style="text-direction:across"/><gap reason="damage" unit="stroke" extent="unknown"/><unclear reason="worn">ᚔᚅᚔ</unclear><gap reason="damage" unit="stroke" extent="unknown"/></persName>
                </ab> 
            </div>                    
            <div type="edition" subtype="transliteration" xml:lang="pgl-Ogam" xml:space="preserve" resp="#POC">
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1" style="text-direction:up"/><persName><gap reason="damage" unit="stroke" extent="unknown"/><unclear reason="worn">C</unclear>CI <w type="formula" lemma="maqqas">MAQ</w><gap reason="damage" unit="stroke" extent="unknown"/>
                    <lb n="2" style="text-direction:across"/><gap reason="damage" unit="stroke" extent="unknown"/><unclear reason="worn">INI</unclear><gap reason="damage" unit="stroke" extent="unknown"/></persName>
                </ab>
                <ab type="list">[...]C̣CI MAQ[...] [...]ỊṆỊ[...] </ab>
            </div>
            <div type="apparatus">
                <listApp>
                <app n="1">
<note>For the second fragment, Macalister (1945, 54) suggested a reading INI and while there does appear to be 2 or possibly 3 notches, it is unclear whether 4 or 5 scores follow, before a further possible 2 notches.</note>                    
                </app>
                </listApp>
            </div>
            <div type="translation">
                <p>... son of ...?</p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary">
                 <p>The extant inscription does not support linguistic analysis. However, the presence of MAQ suggests that the inscription might have contained the common formula word MAQI or MAQQI for <distinct xml:lang="sga"><ref target="https://dil.ie/31166">mac, macc</ref></distinct> 'son'.</p>
            </div>
